Probably FastAPI needs to implement its own forward annotation evaluation logic, and perhaps a "rebuild" pattern for such use cases. Currently, upon creation of the API route, the `Dependant` instance is not defined correctly:

```python
from __future__ import annotations

from dataclasses import dataclass
from typing import Annotated

from fastapi import Depends, FastAPI

app = FastAPI()

def get_potato() -> Potato:
    return Potato(color='red', size=10)


@app.post('/')
async def read_root(potato: Annotated[Potato, Depends(get_potato)]):
    return {'Hello': 'World'}


@dataclass
class Potato:
    color: str
    size: int

app.routes[-1].dependant
#> Dependant(query_params=[ModelField(field_info=Query(PydanticUndefined), name='potato', mode='validation')] ,...)
``` 

Also note that the logic to evaluate forward annotations is too naive:

https://github.com/fastapi/fastapi/blob/d7f88623e1304667c67da17dfd278b5099522ef9/fastapi/dependencies/utils.py#L247-L251

and as such the following also fails even if `Potato` is defined *before*:

```python
